				=09
					<div id=3D"mw-content-text" class=3D"mw-body-content"><div class=3D"mw=
-content-ltr mw-parser-output" lang=3D"en" dir=3D"ltr"><div class=3D"shortd=
escription nomobile noexcerpt noprint searchaux" style=3D"display:none">Met=
hod of exchanging cryptographic keys</div>
<p class=3D"mw-empty-elt">
</p>
<figure class=3D"mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:DiffieHellman.png" class=3D"mw-file-descripti=
on"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c8/D=
iffieHellman.png/500px-DiffieHellman.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"409" =
height=3D"359" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"944" data-file-=
height=3D"828"></a><figcaption>With Diffie=E2=80=93Hellman key exchange, tw=
o parties arrive at a common secret key, without passing the common secret =
key across the public channel.</figcaption></figure>
<p><b>Diffie=E2=80=93Hellman</b> (<b>DH</b>) <b>key exchange</b><sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Di=
ffie%E2%80%93Hellman_key_exchange#cite_note-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>nb 1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> is a mathemati=
cal method of securely generating a symmetric <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Cryptographic_key" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Cryptographic=
 key">cryptographic key</a> over a public channel and was one of the first =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Public-key_cryptography" title=3D"=
Public-key cryptography">protocols</a> as conceived by <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ralph_Merkle" title=3D"Ralph Merkle">Ralph Merkle</a> =
and named after <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Whitfield_Diffie" =
title=3D"Whitfield Diffie">Whitfield Diffie</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Martin_Hellman" title=3D"Martin Hellman">Martin Hellman</=
a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Merkle_1978_2-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diffie%E2%80%93Hellman_key_exchange#cite_note-Mer=
kle_1978-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup> DH is one of the earliest practical examples of publ=
ic key exchange implemented within the field of cryptography. Published in =
1976 by Diffie and Hellman, this is the earliest publicly known work that p=
roposed the idea of a private key and a corresponding public key.
</p><p>Traditionally, secure encrypted communication between two parties re=
quired that they first exchange keys by some secure physical means, such as=
 paper key lists transported by a trusted <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Courier" title=3D"Courier">courier</a>. The Diffie=E2=80=93Hellman =
key exchange method allows two parties that have no prior knowledge of each=
 other to jointly establish a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shar=
ed_secret" title=3D"Shared secret">shared secret</a> key over an <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Insecure_channel" class=3D"mw-redirect" titl=
e=3D"Insecure channel">insecure channel</a>. This key can then be used to e=
ncrypt subsequent communications using a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Symmetric-key_algorithm" title=3D"Symmetric-key algorithm">symmetric=
-key</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cipher" title=3D"Cipher">=
cipher</a>.
</p><p>Diffie=E2=80=93Hellman is used to secure a variety of <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet" title=3D"Internet">Internet</a> servic=
es. However, research published in October 2015 suggests that the parameter=
s in use for many DH Internet applications at that time are not strong enou=
gh to prevent compromise by very well-funded attackers, such as the securit=
y services of some countries.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-imperfectfs_3-0" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diffie%E2%80%93Hellman_=
key_exchange#cite_note-imperfectfs-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The scheme was published by Whitfield Diffie and Martin Hellman in 1=
976,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Diffie_1976_4-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diffie%E2%80%93Hellman_key_exchange#cite_note-Di=
ffie_1976-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">]</span></a></sup> but in 1997 it was revealed that <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_H._Ellis" title=3D"James H. Ellis">James H. El=
lis</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-5" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Diffie%E2%80%93Hellman_key_exchange#cite_note-5"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Clifford_Cocks" title=3D"Cliffor=
d Cocks">Clifford Cocks</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M=
alcolm_J._Williamson" title=3D"Malcolm J. Williamson">Malcolm J. Williamson=
</a> of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Government_Communications_=
Headquarters" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Government Communications Head=
quarters">GCHQ</a>, the British signals intelligence agency, had previously=
 shown in 1969<sup id=3D"cite_ref-6" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diffie%E2%80%93Hellman_key_exchange#cite_note-6"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup> how public-key cryptography could be achieved.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-7=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diffie%E2%80=
%93Hellman_key_exchange#cite_note-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Although Diffie=E2=80=93Hellman key exchange itself is a non-authent=
icated <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Key-agreement_protocol" tit=
le=3D"Key-agreement protocol">key-agreement protocol</a>, it provides the b=
asis for a variety of authenticated protocols, and is used to provide <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Forward_secrecy" title=3D"Forward secre=
cy">forward secrecy</a> in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Transpo=
rt_Layer_Security" title=3D"Transport Layer Security">Transport Layer Secur=
ity</a>'s <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ephemeral_key" title=3D"=
Ephemeral key">ephemeral</a> modes (referred to as EDH or DHE depending on =
the cipher suite).
</p><p>The method was followed shortly afterwards by <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/RSA_(algorithm)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"RSA (alg=
orithm)">RSA</a>, an implementation of public-key cryptography using asymme=
tric algorithms.
</p><p>Expired US patent 4200770<sup id=3D"cite_ref-8" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diffie%E2%80%93Hellman_key_exchang=
e#cite_note-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup> from 1977 describes the now public-domain algorit=
hm. It credits Hellman, Diffie, and Merkle as inventors.
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Name">Name</h2><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DDiffie%E2%80%93Hellman_key=
_exchange&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: Name"><=
span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span><=
/div>
<p>In 2006, Hellman suggested the algorithm be called <b>Diffie=E2=80=93Hel=
lman=E2=80=93Merkle key exchange</b> in recognition of <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ralph_Merkle" title=3D"Ralph Merkle">Ralph Merkle</a>'=
s contribution to the invention of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Public-key_cryptography" title=3D"Public-key cryptography">public-key cryp=
tography</a> (Hellman, 2006), writing:
</p>
<blockquote class=3D"templatequote"><p>The system ... has since become know=
n as Diffie=E2=80=93Hellman key exchange. While that system was first descr=
ibed in a paper by Diffie and me, it is a public key distribution system, a=
 concept developed by Merkle, and hence should be called 'Diffie=E2=80=93He=
llman=E2=80=93Merkle key exchange' if names are to be associated with it. I=
 hope this small pulpit might help in that endeavor to recognize Merkle's e=
qual contribution to the invention of public key cryptography.<sup id=3D"ci=
te_ref-Hellman2002_9-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Diffie%E2%80%93Hellman_key_exchange#cite_note-Hellman2002-9"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup></p></blockquote>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Description">Description</h=
2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</=
span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DDiffie%E2%80%9=
3Hellman_key_exchange&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit sect=
ion: Description"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">]</span></span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"General_overview">General o=
verview</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DDiff=
ie%E2%80%93Hellman_key_exchange&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" title=3D=
"Edit section: General overview"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-edi=
tsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F=
ile:Diffie-Hellman_Key_Exchange.svg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=
=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/46/Diffie-Hellma=
n_Key_Exchange.svg/250px-Diffie-Hellman_Key_Exchange.svg.png" decoding=3D"a=
sync" width=3D"250" height=3D"375" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-widt=
h=3D"427" data-file-height=3D"641"></a><figcaption>Illustration of the conc=
ept behind Diffie=E2=80=93Hellman key exchange</figcaption></figure>
<p>Diffie=E2=80=93Hellman key exchange establishes a shared secret between =
two parties that can be used for secret communication for exchanging data o=
ver a public network. An analogy illustrates the concept of public key exch=
ange by using colors instead of very large numbers:
</p><p>The process begins by having the two parties, <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Alice_and_Bob" title=3D"Alice and Bob">Alice and Bob</a>=
, publicly agree on an arbitrary starting color that does not need to be ke=
pt secret. In this example, the color is yellow. Each person also selects a=
 secret color that they keep to themselves =E2=80=93 in this case, red and =
cyan. The crucial part of the process is that Alice and Bob each mix their =
own secret color together with their mutually shared color, resulting in or=
ange-tan and light-blue mixtures respectively, and then publicly exchange t=
he two mixed colors. Finally, each of them mixes the color they received fr=
om the partner with their own private color. The result is a final color mi=
xture (yellow-brown in this case) that is identical to their partner's fina=
l color mixture.
</p><p>If a third party listened to the exchange, they would only know the =
common color (yellow) and the first mixed colors (orange-tan and light-blue=
), but it would be very hard for them to find out the final secret color (y=
ellow-brown). Bringing the analogy back to a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Real-life" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Real-life">real-life</=
a> exchange using large numbers rather than colors, this determination is c=
omputationally expensive; it is impossible to compute in a practical amount=
 of time even for modern <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Supercomp=
uter" title=3D"Supercomputer">supercomputers</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Cryptographic_explanation">=
