<p>The simplest and the original implementation,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Diffie_=
1976_4-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diff=
ie%E2%80%93Hellman_key_exchange#cite_note-Diffie_1976-4"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> later f=
ormalized as <b>Finite Field Diffie=E2=80=93Hellman</b> in RFC 7919,<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-10" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Diffie%E2%80%93Hellman_key_exchange#cite_note-10"><span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">[</span>9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> of the prot=
ocol uses the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multiplicative_group=
_of_integers_modulo_n" title=3D"Multiplicative group of integers modulo n">=
multiplicative group of integers modulo</a> <i>p</i>, where <i>p</i> is <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prime_number" title=3D"Prime number">=
prime</a>, and <i>g</i> is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Primi=
tive_root_modulo_n" title=3D"Primitive root modulo n">primitive root modulo=
</a> <i>p</i>. To guard against potential vulnerabilities, it is recommende=
d to use prime numbers of at least 2048 bits in length. This increases the =
difficulty for an adversary attempting to compute the discrete logarithm an=
d compromise the shared secret. These two values are chosen in this way to =
ensure that the resulting shared secret can take on any value from 1 to <sp=
an class=3D"nowrap"><i>p</i> =E2=88=92 1</span>. Here is an example of the =
