<p>Only <i>a</i> and <i>b</i> are kept secret. All the other values =E2=80=
=93 <i>p</i>, <i>g</i>, <i>g<sup>a</sup></i> mod <i>p</i>, and <i>g<sup>b</=
sup></i> mod <i>p</i> =E2=80=93 are sent in the clear. The strength of the =
scheme comes from the fact that <i>g<sup>ab</sup></i> mod <i>p</i> =3D <i>g=
<sup>ba</sup></i> mod <i>p</i> take extremely long times to compute by any =
known algorithm just from the knowledge of <i>p</i>, <i>g</i>, <i>g<sup>a</=
sup></i> mod <i>p</i>, and <i>g<sup>b</sup></i> mod <i>p</i>. Such a functi=
on that is easy to compute but hard to invert is called a <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/One-way_function" title=3D"One-way function">one-wa=
y function</a>. Once Alice and Bob compute the shared secret they can use i=
t as an encryption key, known only to them, for sending messages across the=
 same open communications channel.
</p><p>Of course, much larger values of <i>a</i>, <i>b</i>, and <i>p</i> wo=
uld be needed to make this example secure, since there are only 23 possible=
 results of <i>n</i> mod 23. However, if <i>p</i> is a prime of at least 60=
0 digits, then even the fastest modern computers using the fastest known al=
gorithm cannot find <i>a</i> given only <i>g</i>, <i>p</i> and <i>g<sup>a</=
sup></i> mod <i>p</i>. Such a problem is called the <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Discrete_logarithm_problem" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Discrete logarithm problem">discrete logarithm problem</a>.<sup id=3D"c=
ite_ref-imperfectfs_3-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Diffie%E2%80%93Hellman_key_exchange#cite_note-imperfectfs-3"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup> The computation of <i>g<sup>a</sup></i> mod <i>p</i> is known as <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Modular_exponentiation" title=3D"Mod=
ular exponentiation">modular exponentiation</a> and can be done efficiently=
 even for large numbers.
Note that <i>g</i> need not be large at all, and in practice is usually a s=
mall integer (like 2, 3, ...).
</p>
