<p>Now <i><b><link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:Tem=
plateStyles:r1308985496"><span class=3D"red-invert">s</span></b></i> is the=
 shared secret key and it is known to both Alice and Bob, but <i>not</i> to=
 Eve. Note that it is not helpful for Eve to compute <i><link rel=3D"mw-ded=
uplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1308985496"><span c=
lass=3D"blue-invert">AB</span></i>, which equals <i><link rel=3D"mw-dedupli=
cated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1308985496"><span class=
=3D"blue-invert">g</span></i><sup><i><b><link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline=
-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1308985496"><span class=3D"red-inve=
rt">a</span></b></i>+<i><b><link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=
=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1308985496"><span class=3D"red-invert">b</span>=
</b></i></sup> mod <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-da=
ta:TemplateStyles:r1308985496"><span class=3D"blue-invert">p</span>.
</p><p>Note: It should be difficult for Alice to solve for Bob's private ke=
y or for Bob to solve for Alice's private key. If it is not difficult for A=
lice to solve for Bob's private key (or vice versa), then an eavesdropper, =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alice_and_Bob#Cast_of_characters" =
title=3D"Alice and Bob">Eve</a>, may simply substitute her own private / pu=
blic key pair, plug Bob's public key into her private key, produce a fake s=
hared secret key, and solve for Bob's private key (and use that to solve fo=
r the shared secret key). <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alice_an=
d_Bob#Cast_of_characters" title=3D"Alice and Bob">Eve</a> may attempt to ch=
oose a public / private key pair that will make it easy for her to solve fo=
r Bob's private key.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Generalization_to_finite_cy=
clic_groups">Generalization to finite cyclic groups</h3><span class=3D"mw-e=
ditsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DDiffie%E2%80%93Hellman_key_exchange=
&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D6" title=3D"Edit section: Generalization t=
o finite cyclic groups"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-=
bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Here is a more general description of the protocol:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-1=
1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diffie%E2%8=
0%93Hellman_key_exchange#cite_note-11"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span=
>10<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<ol><li>Alice and Bob agree on a natural number <i>n</i> and a <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Generating_set_of_a_group" title=3D"Generating=
 set of a group">generating</a> element <i>g</i> in the finite <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cyclic_group" title=3D"Cyclic group">cyclic gr=
oup</a> <i>G</i> of order <i>n</i>. (This is usually done long before the r=
est of the protocol; <i>g</i> and <i>n</i> are assumed to be known by all a=
ttackers.) The group <i>G</i> is written multiplicatively.</li>
<li>Alice picks a random <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Natural_n=
umber" title=3D"Natural number">natural number</a> <i>a</i> with 1 &lt; <i>=
a</i> &lt; <i>n</i>, and sends the element <i>g<sup>a</sup></i> of <i>G</i>=
 to Bob.</li>
<li>Bob picks a random natural number <i>b</i> with 1 &lt; <i>b</i> &lt; <i=
>n</i>, and sends the element <i>g<sup>b</sup></i> of <i>G</i> to Alice.</l=
i>
<li>Alice computes the element <span class=3D"texhtml">(<i>g<sup>b</sup></i=
>)<sup><i>a</i></sup> =3D <i>g<sup>ba</sup></i></span> of G.</li>
<li>Bob computes the element <span class=3D"texhtml">(<i>g<sup>a</sup></i>)=
<sup><i>b</i></sup> =3D <i>g<sup>ab</sup></i></span> of G.</li></ol>
<p>Both Alice and Bob are now in possession of the group element <i>g<sup>a=
b</sup></i> =3D <i>g<sup>ba</sup></i>, which can serve as the shared secret=
 key. The group <i>G</i> satisfies the requisite condition for <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Secure_communication" title=3D"Secure communic=
ation">secure communication</a> as long as there is no efficient algorithm =
for determining <i>g<sup>ab</sup></i> given <i>g</i>, <i>g<sup>a</sup></i>,=
 and <i>g<sup>b</sup></i>.
</p><p>For example, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elliptic-c=
urve_Diffie%E2%80%93Hellman" title=3D"Elliptic-curve Diffie=E2=80=93Hellman=
">elliptic curve Diffie=E2=80=93Hellman</a> protocol is a variant that repr=
esents an element of G as a point on an elliptic curve instead of as an int=
eger modulo n.&nbsp;Variants using <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Hyperelliptic_curve_cryptography" title=3D"Hyperelliptic curve cryptograph=
y">hyperelliptic curves</a> have also been proposed. The <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Supersingular_isogeny_key_exchange" title=3D"Supersi=
ngular isogeny key exchange">supersingular isogeny key exchange</a> is a Di=
ffie=E2=80=93Hellman variant that was designed to be secure against <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quantum_computers" class=3D"mw-redirect" =
title=3D"Quantum computers">quantum computers</a>, but it was broken in Jul=
y 2022.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-castryckdecru2023_12-0" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diffie%E2%80%93Hellman_key_exchange#ci=
te_note-castryckdecru2023-12"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Ephemeral_and/or_static_key=
s"><span id=3D"Ephemeral_and.2For_static_keys"></span>Ephemeral and/or stat=
ic keys</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DDiff=
ie%E2%80%93Hellman_key_exchange&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D7" title=3D=
"Edit section: Ephemeral and/or static keys"><span>edit</span></a><span cla=
ss=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The used keys can either be ephemeral or static (long term) key, but cou=
ld even be mixed, so called semi-static DH. These variants have different p=
roperties and hence different use cases. An overview over many variants and=
 some also discussions can for example be found in NIST SP 800-56A.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-13" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Diffie%E2%80%93Hellman_key_exchange#cite_note-13"><span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">[</span>12<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> A basic li=
st:
</p>
<ol><li>ephemeral, ephemeral: Usually used for key agreement. Provides <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Forward_secrecy" title=3D"Forward secr=
ecy">forward secrecy</a>, but no <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A=
uthentication" title=3D"Authentication">authenticity</a>.</li>
<li>static, static: Would generate a long term shared secret. Does not prov=
ide forward secrecy, but implicit authenticity. Since the keys are static i=
t would for example not protect against <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Replay_attack" title=3D"Replay attack">replay-attacks</a>.</li>
<li>ephemeral, static: For example, used in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/ElGamal_encryption" title=3D"ElGamal encryption">ElGamal encrypti=
on</a> or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integrated_Encryption_Sc=
heme" title=3D"Integrated Encryption Scheme">Integrated Encryption Scheme (=
IES)</a>. If used in key agreement it could provide implicit one-sided auth=
enticity (the ephemeral side could verify the authenticity of the static si=
de). No forward secrecy is provided.</li></ol>
<p>It is possible to use ephemeral and static keys in one key agreement to =
provide more security as for example shown in NIST SP 800-56A, but it is al=
so possible to combine those in a single DH key exchange, which is then cal=
led triple DH (3-DH).
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Triple_Diffie=E2=80=93Hellm=
an_(3-DH)"><span id=3D"Triple_Diffie.E2.80.93Hellman_.283-DH.29"></span>Tri=
ple Diffie=E2=80=93Hellman (3-DH)</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/w/index.php?title=3DDiffie%E2%80%93Hellman_key_exchange&amp;action=3Dedit=
&amp;section=3D8" title=3D"Edit section: Triple Diffie=E2=80=93Hellman (3-D=
H)"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></s=
pan></div>
<p>In 1997 a kind of triple DH was proposed by Simon Blake-Wilson, Don John=
son and Alfred Menezes,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-14" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diffie%E2%80%93Hellman_key_exchange#cite_=
note-14"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">]</span></a></sup> which was improved by C. Kudla and K. G. Paterson in 2=
005<sup id=3D"cite_ref-15" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Diffie%E2%80%93Hellman_key_exchange#cite_note-15"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 and shown to be secure.
</p><p>The long term secret keys of Alice and Bob are denoted by <i>a</i> a=
nd <i>b</i> respectively, with public keys <i>A</i> and <i>B</i>, as well a=
s the ephemeral key pairs (<i>x</i>, <i>X</i>) and (<i>y</i>, <i>Y</i>). Th=
en protocol is:
</p>
