<p>The long term public keys need to be transferred somehow. That can be do=
ne beforehand in a separate, trusted channel, or the public keys can be enc=
rypted using some partial key agreement to preserve anonymity. For more of =
such details as well as other improvements like <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Side-channel_attack" title=3D"Side-channel attack">side chann=
el protection</a> or explicit <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Key_=
(cryptography)" title=3D"Key (cryptography)">key confirmation</a>, as well =
as early messages and additional password authentication, see e.g. US paten=
t "Advanced modular handshake for key agreement and optional authentication=
".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-16" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Diffie%E2%80%93Hellman_key_exchange#cite_note-16"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>15<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Extended_Triple_Diffie=E2=
=80=93Hellman_(X3DH)"><span id=3D"Extended_Triple_Diffie.E2.80.93Hellman_.2=
8X3DH.29"></span>Extended Triple Diffie=E2=80=93Hellman (X3DH)</h3><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DDiffie%E2%80%93Hellman_k=
ey_exchange&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D9" title=3D"Edit section: Exten=
ded Triple Diffie=E2=80=93Hellman (X3DH)"><span>edit</span></a><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>X3DH was initially proposed as part of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Double_Ratchet_Algorithm" title=3D"Double Ratchet Algorithm">Do=
uble Ratchet Algorithm</a> used in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Signal_Protocol" title=3D"Signal Protocol">Signal Protocol</a>. The pr=
otocol offers forward secrecy and cryptographic deniability. It operates on=
 an elliptic curve.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-x3dh_17-0" class=3D"reference"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diffie%E2%80%93Hellman_key_exchange#cit=
e_note-x3dh-17"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>16<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The protocol uses five public keys. Alice has an identity key IK<sub=
>A</sub> and an ephemeral key EK<sub>A</sub>. Bob has an identity key IK<su=
b>B</sub>, a signed prekey SPK<sub>B</sub>, and a one-time prekey OPK<sub>B=
</sub>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-x3dh_17-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diffie%E2%80%93Hellman_key_exchange#cite_note-x3dh-=
17"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>16<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup> Bob first publishes his three keys to a server, which Alice=
 downloads and verifies the signature on. Alice then initiates the exchange=
 to Bob.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-x3dh_17-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diffie%E2%80%93Hellman_key_exchange#cite_note-x3dh=
-17"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>16<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup> The OPK is optional.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-x3dh_17-3" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diffie%E2%80%93Hell=
man_key_exchange#cite_note-x3dh-17"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>16=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Operation_with_more_than_tw=
o_parties">Operation with more than two parties</h2><span class=3D"mw-edits=
ection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DDiffie%E2%80%93Hellman_key_exchange&amp=
;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D10" title=3D"Edit section: Operation with more=
 than two parties"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brack=
et">]</span></span></div>
<p>Diffie=E2=80=93Hellman key agreement is not limited to negotiating a key=
 shared by only two participants. Any number of users can take part in an a=
greement by performing iterations of the agreement protocol and exchanging =
intermediate data (which does not itself need to be kept secret). For examp=
le, Alice, Bob, and Carol could participate in a Diffie=E2=80=93Hellman agr=
eement as follows, with all operations taken to be modulo <i>p</i>:
</p>
<ol><li>The parties agree on the algorithm parameters <i>p</i> and <i>g</i>=
.</li>
<li>The parties generate their private keys, named <i>a</i>, <i>b</i>, and =
<i>c</i>.</li>
<li>Alice computes <span class=3D"texhtml"><var style=3D"padding-right: 1px=
;">g<sup>a</sup></var> mod <var style=3D"padding-right: 1px;">p</var></span=
> and sends it to Bob.</li>
<li>Bob computes <span class=3D"texhtml">(<var style=3D"padding-right: 1px;=
">g<sup>a</sup></var>)<sup><var style=3D"padding-right: 1px;">b</var></sup>=
 mod <var style=3D"padding-right: 1px;">p</var> =3D <var style=3D"padding-r=
ight: 1px;">g<sup>ab</sup></var> mod <var style=3D"padding-right: 1px;">p</=
var></span> and sends it to Carol.</li>
<li>Carol computes <span class=3D"texhtml">(<var style=3D"padding-right: 1p=
x;">g<sup>ab</sup></var>)<sup><var style=3D"padding-right: 1px;">c</var></s=
up> mod <var style=3D"padding-right: 1px;">p</var> =3D <var style=3D"paddin=
g-right: 1px;">g<sup>abc</sup></var> mod <var style=3D"padding-right: 1px;"=
>p</var></span> and uses it as her secret.</li>
<li>Bob computes <span class=3D"texhtml">g<sup>b</sup> mod <var style=3D"pa=
dding-right: 1px;">p</var></span> and sends it to Carol.</li>
<li>Carol computes <span class=3D"texhtml">(<var style=3D"padding-right: 1p=
x;">g<sup>b</sup></var>)<sup><var style=3D"padding-right: 1px;">c</var></su=
p> mod <var style=3D"padding-right: 1px;">p</var> =3D <var style=3D"padding=
-right: 1px;">g<sup>bc</sup></var> mod <var style=3D"padding-right: 1px;">p=
</var></span> and sends it to Alice.</li>
<li>Alice computes <span class=3D"texhtml">(<var style=3D"padding-right: 1p=
x;">g<sup>bc</sup></var>)<sup><var style=3D"padding-right: 1px;">a</var></s=
up> mod <var style=3D"padding-right: 1px;">p</var> =3D <var style=3D"paddin=
g-right: 1px;">g<sup>bca</sup></var> mod <var style=3D"padding-right: 1px;"=
>p</var> =3D <var style=3D"padding-right: 1px;">g<sup>abc</sup></var> mod <=
var style=3D"padding-right: 1px;">p</var></span> and uses it as her secret.=
</li>
<li>Carol computes <span class=3D"texhtml"><var style=3D"padding-right: 1px=
;">g<sup>c</sup></var> mod <var style=3D"padding-right: 1px;">p</var></span=
> and sends it to Alice.</li>
<li>Alice computes <span class=3D"texhtml">(<var style=3D"padding-right: 1p=
x;">g<sup>c</sup></var>)<sup><var style=3D"padding-right: 1px;">a</var></su=
p> mod <var style=3D"padding-right: 1px;">p</var> =3D <var style=3D"padding=
-right: 1px;">g<sup>ca</sup></var> mod <var style=3D"padding-right: 1px;">p=
</var></span> and sends it to Bob.</li>
<li>Bob computes <span class=3D"texhtml">(<var style=3D"padding-right: 1px;=
">g<sup>ca</sup></var>)<sup><var style=3D"padding-right: 1px;">b</var></sup=
> mod <var style=3D"padding-right: 1px;">p</var> =3D <var style=3D"padding-=
right: 1px;">g<sup>cab</sup></var> mod <var style=3D"padding-right: 1px;">p=
</var> =3D <var style=3D"padding-right: 1px;">g<sup>abc</sup></var> mod <va=
r style=3D"padding-right: 1px;">p</var></span> and uses it as his secret.</=
li></ol>
<p>An eavesdropper has been able to see <span class=3D"texhtml"><var style=
=3D"padding-right: 1px;">g<sup>a</sup></var> mod <var style=3D"padding-righ=
t: 1px;">p</var></span>, <span class=3D"texhtml"><var style=3D"padding-righ=
t: 1px;">g<sup>b</sup></var> mod <var style=3D"padding-right: 1px;">p</var>=
</span>, <span class=3D"texhtml"><var style=3D"padding-right: 1px;">g<sup>c=
</sup></var> mod <var style=3D"padding-right: 1px;">p</var></span>, <span c=
lass=3D"texhtml"><var style=3D"padding-right: 1px;">g<sup>ab</sup></var> mo=
d <var style=3D"padding-right: 1px;">p</var></span>, <span class=3D"texhtml=
"><var style=3D"padding-right: 1px;">g<sup>ac</sup></var> mod <var style=3D=
"padding-right: 1px;">p</var></span>, and <span class=3D"texhtml"><var styl=
e=3D"padding-right: 1px;">g<sup>bc</sup></var> mod <var style=3D"padding-ri=
ght: 1px;">p</var></span>, but cannot use any combination of these to effic=
iently reproduce <span class=3D"texhtml"><var style=3D"padding-right: 1px;"=
>g<sup>abc</sup></var> mod <var style=3D"padding-right: 1px;">p</var></span=
>.
</p><p>To extend this mechanism to larger groups, two basic principles must=
 be followed:
</p>
<ul><li>Starting with an "empty" key consisting only of <i>g</i>, the secre=
t is made by raising the current value to every participant's private expon=
ent once, in any order (the first such exponentiation yields the participan=
t's own public key).</li>
<li>Any intermediate value (having up to <i>N</i>=E2=88=921 exponents appli=
ed, where <i>N</i> is the number of participants in the group) may be revea=
led publicly, but the final value (having had all <i>N</i> exponents applie=
d) constitutes the shared secret and hence must never be revealed publicly.=
 Thus, each user must obtain their copy of the secret by applying their own=
 private key last (otherwise there would be no way for the last contributor=
 to communicate the final key to its recipient, as that last contributor wo=
uld have turned the key into the very secret the group wished to protect).<=
/li></ul>
<p>These principles leave open various options for choosing in which order =
participants contribute to keys. The simplest and most obvious solution is =
to arrange the <i>N</i> participants in a circle and have <i>N</i> keys rot=
ate around the circle, until eventually every key has been contributed to b=
y all <i>N</i> participants (ending with its owner) and each participant ha=
s contributed to <i>N</i> keys (ending with their own). However, this requi=
res that every participant perform <i>N</i> modular exponentiations.
</p><p>By choosing a more desirable order, and relying on the fact that key=
s can be duplicated, it is possible to reduce the number of modular exponen=
tiations performed by each participant to <span class=3D"texhtml">log<sub>2=
</sub>(<i>N</i>) + 1</span> using a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Divide_and_conquer_algorithms" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Divide and =
conquer algorithms">divide-and-conquer-style</a> approach, given here for e=
ight participants:
</p>
<ol><li>Participants A, B, C, and D each perform one exponentiation, yieldi=
ng <span class=3D"texhtml"><var style=3D"padding-right: 1px;">g<sup>abcd</s=
up></var></span>; this value is sent to E, F, G, and H. In return, particip=
ants A, B, C, and D receive <span class=3D"texhtml"><var style=3D"padding-r=
ight: 1px;">g<sup>efgh</sup></var></span>.</li>
<li>Participants A and B each perform one exponentiation, yielding <span cl=
ass=3D"texhtml"><var style=3D"padding-right: 1px;">g<sup>efghab</sup></var>=
</span>, which they send to C and D, while C and D do the same, yielding <s=
pan class=3D"texhtml"><var style=3D"padding-right: 1px;">g<sup>efghcd</sup>=
</var></span>, which they send to A and B.</li>
<li>Participant A performs an exponentiation, yielding <span class=3D"texht=
ml"><var style=3D"padding-right: 1px;">g<sup>efghcda</sup></var></span>, wh=
ich it sends to B; similarly, B sends <span class=3D"texhtml"><var style=3D=
"padding-right: 1px;">g<sup>efghcdb</sup></var></span> to A. C and D do sim=
ilarly.</li>
<li>Participant A performs one final exponentiation, yielding the secret <s=
pan class=3D"texhtml"><var style=3D"padding-right: 1px;">g<sup>efghcdba</su=
p></var></span> =3D <span class=3D"texhtml"><var style=3D"padding-right: 1p=
x;">g<sup>abcdefgh</sup></var></span>, while B does the same to get <span c=
lass=3D"texhtml"><var style=3D"padding-right: 1px;">g<sup>efghcdab</sup></v=
ar></span> =3D <span class=3D"texhtml"><var style=3D"padding-right: 1px;">g=
<sup>abcdefgh</sup></var></span>; again, C and D do similarly.</li>
<li>Participants E through H simultaneously perform the same operations usi=
ng <span class=3D"texhtml"><var style=3D"padding-right: 1px;">g<sup>abcd</s=
up></var></span> as their starting point.</li></ol>
<p>Once this operation has been completed all participants will possess the=
 secret <span class=3D"texhtml"><var style=3D"padding-right: 1px;">g<sup>ab=
cdefgh</sup></var></span>, but each participant will have performed only fo=
ur modular exponentiations, rather than the eight implied by a simple circu=
lar arrangement.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Security_and_practical_cons=
iderations">Security and practical considerations</h2><span class=3D"mw-edi=
tsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DDiffie%E2%80%93Hellman_key_exchange&a=
mp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D11" title=3D"Edit section: Security and prac=
tical considerations"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The protocol is considered secure against eavesdroppers if <i>G</i> and =
<i>g</i> are chosen properly. In particular, the order of the group G must =
be large, particularly if the same group is used for large amounts of traff=
ic. The eavesdropper has to solve the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Diffie%E2%80%93Hellman_problem" title=3D"Diffie=E2=80=93Hellman problem=
">Diffie=E2=80=93Hellman problem</a> to obtain <i>g</i><sup><i>ab</i></sup>=
. This is currently considered difficult for groups whose order is large en=
ough. An efficient algorithm to solve the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Discrete_logarithm_problem" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Discrete=
 logarithm problem">discrete logarithm problem</a> would make it easy to co=
mpute <i>a</i> or <i>b</i> and solve the Diffie=E2=80=93Hellman problem, ma=
king this and many other public key cryptosystems insecure. Fields of small=
 characteristic may be less secure.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-18" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diffie%E2%80%93Hellman_key_exc=
hange#cite_note-18"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>17<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Order_(group_theory)" t=
itle=3D"Order (group theory)">order</a> of <i>G</i> should have a large pri=
me factor to prevent use of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Po=
hlig%E2%80%93Hellman_algorithm" title=3D"Pohlig=E2=80=93Hellman algorithm">=
Pohlig=E2=80=93Hellman algorithm</a> to obtain <i>a</i> or <i>b</i>. For th=
is reason, a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sophie_Germain_prime"=
 class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Sophie Germain prime">Sophie Germain prime<=
/a> <i>q</i> is sometimes used to calculate <span class=3D"nowrap"><i>p</i>=
 =3D 2<i>q</i> + 1</span>, called a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Safe_prime" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Safe prime">safe prime</a>, si=
nce the order of <i>G</i> is then only divisible by 2 and <i>q</i>. Sometim=
es <i>g</i> is chosen to generate the order <i>q</i> subgroup of <i>G</i>, =
rather than <i>G</i>, so that the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Legendre_symbol" title=3D"Legendre symbol">Legendre symbol</a> of <i>g<sup>=
a</sup></i> never reveals the low order bit of <i>a</i>. A protocol using s=
uch a choice is for example <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Intern=
et_Key_Exchange" title=3D"Internet Key Exchange">IKEv2</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-19" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diffie=
%E2%80%93Hellman_key_exchange#cite_note-19"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>18<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The generator <i>g</i> is often a small integer such as 2. Because o=
f the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Random_self-reducibility" ti=
tle=3D"Random self-reducibility">random self-reducibility</a> of the discre=
te logarithm problem a small <i>g</i> is equally secure as any other genera=
tor of the same group.
</p><p>If Alice and Bob use <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Random=
_number_generator" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Random number generator">=
random number generators</a> whose outputs are not completely random and ca=
n be predicted to some extent, then it is much easier to eavesdrop.
</p><p>In the original description, the Diffie=E2=80=93Hellman exchange by =
itself does not provide <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Authentica=
tion" title=3D"Authentication">authentication</a> of the communicating part=
ies and can be vulnerable to a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Man=
-in-the-middle_attack" title=3D"Man-in-the-middle attack">man-in-the-middle=
 attack</a>.
Mallory (an active attacker executing the man-in-the-middle attack) may est=
ablish two distinct key exchanges, one with Alice and the other with Bob, e=
ffectively masquerading as Alice to Bob, and vice versa, allowing her to de=
crypt, then re-encrypt, the messages passed between them. Note that Mallory=
 must be in the middle from the beginning and continuing to be so, actively=
 decrypting and re-encrypting messages every time Alice and Bob communicate=
. If she arrives after the keys have been generated and the encrypted conve=
rsation between Alice and Bob has already begun, the attack cannot succeed.=
 If she is ever absent, her previous presence is then revealed to Alice and=
 Bob. They will know that all of their private conversations had been inter=
cepted and decoded by someone in the channel. In most cases it will not hel=
p them get Mallory's private key, even if she used the same key for both ex=
changes.
</p><p>A method to authenticate the communicating parties to each other is =
generally needed to prevent this type of attack. Variants of Diffie=E2=80=
=93Hellman, such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Station-to-Sta=
tion_protocol" title=3D"Station-to-Station protocol">STS protocol</a>, may =
be used instead to avoid these types of attacks.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Denial-of-service_attack">D=
enial-of-service attack</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"m=
w-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.=
php?title=3DDiffie%E2%80%93Hellman_key_exchange&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;secti=
on=3D12" title=3D"Edit section: Denial-of-service attack"><span>edit</span>=
</a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>A <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Common_Vulnerabilities_and_Ex=
posures" title=3D"Common Vulnerabilities and Exposures">CVE</a> released in=
 2021 (<i><a rel=3D"nofollow" class=3D"external text" href=3D"https://nvd.n=
ist.gov/vuln/detail/CVE-2002-20001">CVE-2002-20001</a></i>) disclosed a <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denial-of-service_attack" title=3D"De=
nial-of-service attack">denial-of-service attack</a> (DoS) against the prot=
ocol variants using ephemeral keys, called D(HE)at attack.<sup id=3D"cite_r=
ef-dheatattack_20-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Diffie%E2%80%93Hellman_key_exchange#cite_note-dheatattack-20"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>19<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup> The attack exploits that the Diffie=E2=80=93Hellman key exchange allo=
ws attackers to send arbitrary numbers that are actually not public keys, t=
riggering expensive modular exponentiation calculations on the victim's sid=
e. Another CVEs release disclosed that the Diffie=E2=80=93Hellman key excha=
nge implementations may use long private exponents  (<i><a rel=3D"nofollow"=
 class=3D"external text" href=3D"https://nvd.nist.gov/vuln/detail/CVE-2022-=
40735">CVE-2022-40735</a></i>) that arguably make modular exponentiation ca=
lculations unnecessarily expensive<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Oorschot_Wiener_1996_=
21-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diffie%E=
2%80%93Hellman_key_exchange#cite_note-Oorschot_Wiener_1996-21"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>20<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 or may unnecessarily check a peer's public key (<i><a rel=3D"nofollow" cla=
ss=3D"external text" href=3D"https://nvd.nist.gov/vuln/detail/CVE-2024-4199=
6">CVE-2024-41996</a></i>) which has similar resource requirement as key ca=
lculation using a long exponent.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-22" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diffie%E2%80%93Hellman_key_exchan=
ge#cite_note-22"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>21<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup> An attacker can exploit both vulnerabilities t=
ogether.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Practical_attacks_on_Intern=
et_traffic">Practical attacks on Internet traffic</h3><span class=3D"mw-edi=
tsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DDiffie%E2%80%93Hellman_key_exchange&a=
mp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D13" title=3D"Edit section: Practical attacks=
 on Internet traffic"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/General_number_field_sieve"=
 title=3D"General number field sieve">number field sieve</a> algorithm, whi=
ch is generally the most effective in solving the <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Discrete_logarithm_problem" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"=
Discrete logarithm problem">discrete logarithm problem</a>, consists of fou=
r computational steps. The first three steps only depend on the order of th=
e group G, not on the specific number whose finite log is desired.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-23" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Diffie%E2%80%93Hellman_key_exchange#cite_note-23"><span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">[</span>22<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> It turns o=
ut that much Internet traffic uses one of a handful of groups that are of o=
rder 1024&nbsp;bits or less.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-imperfectfs_3-2" class=3D"r=
eference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diffie%E2%80%93Hellman_k=
ey_exchange#cite_note-imperfectfs-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> By <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Precomputing" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Precomputing"=
>precomputing</a> the first three steps of the number field sieve for the m=
ost common groups, an attacker need only carry out the last step, which is =
much less computationally expensive than the first three steps, to obtain a=
 specific logarithm. The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logjam_(c=
omputer_security)" title=3D"Logjam (computer security)">Logjam</a> attack u=
sed this vulnerability to compromise a variety of Internet services that al=
lowed the use of groups whose order was a 512-bit prime number, so called <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Export_of_cryptography" title=3D"Ex=
port of cryptography">export grade</a>. The authors needed several thousand=
 CPU cores for a week to precompute data for a single 512-bit prime. Once t=
hat was done, individual logarithms could be solved in about a minute using=
 two 18-core Intel Xeon CPUs.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-imperfectfs_3-3" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diffie%E2%80%93Hellman_=
key_exchange#cite_note-imperfectfs-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>As estimated by the authors behind the Logjam attack, the much more =
difficult precomputation needed to solve the discrete log problem for a 102=
4-bit prime would cost on the order of $100 million, well within the budget=
 of a large national <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Intelligence_=
agency" title=3D"Intelligence agency">intelligence agency</a> such as the U=
.S. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_Security_Agency" titl=
e=3D"National Security Agency">National Security Agency</a> (NSA). The Logj=
am authors speculate that precomputation against widely reused 1024-bit DH =
primes is behind claims in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2010s_g=
lobal_surveillance_disclosures" title=3D"2010s global surveillance disclosu=
res">leaked NSA documents</a> that NSA is able to break much of current cry=
ptography.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-imperfectfs_3-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diffie%E2%80%93Hellman_key_exchange#cite_=
note-imperfectfs-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>To avoid these vulnerabilities, the Logjam authors recommend use of =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elliptic_curve_cryptography" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Elliptic curve cryptography">elliptic curve crypt=
ography</a>, for which no similar attack is known. Failing that, they recom=
mend that the order, <i>p</i>, of the Diffie=E2=80=93Hellman group should b=
e at least 2048&nbsp;bits. They estimate that the pre-computation required =
for a 2048-bit prime is 10<sup>9</sup> times more difficult than for 1024-b=
it primes.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-imperfectfs_3-5" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diffie%E2%80%93Hellman_key_exchange#cite_=
note-imperfectfs-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Security_against_quantum_co=
mputers">Security against quantum computers</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsecti=
on"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DDiffie%E2%80%93Hellman_key_exchange&amp;act=
ion=3Dedit&amp;section=3D14" title=3D"Edit section: Security against quantu=
m computers"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]<=
/span></span></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quantum_computing" title=3D"Qua=
ntum computing">Quantum computers</a> can break public-key cryptographic sc=
hemes, such as RSA, finite-field DH and elliptic-curve DH key-exchange prot=
ocols, using <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shor%27s_algorithm" t=
itle=3D"Shor's algorithm">Shor's algorithm</a> for solving the <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integer_factorization" title=3D"Integer factor=
ization">factoring problem</a>, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Discrete_logarithm" title=3D"Discrete logarithm">discrete logarithm probl=
em</a>, and the period-finding problem. A <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Post-Quantum_Extended_Diffie%E2%80%93Hellman" title=3D"Post-Quantum=
 Extended Diffie=E2=80=93Hellman">post-quantum variant of Diffie-Hellman al=
gorithm</a> was proposed in 2023, and relies on a combination of the quantu=
m-resistant CRYSTALS-Kyber protocol, as well as the old elliptic curve <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/X25519" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D=
"X25519">X25519</a> protocol.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Other_uses">Other uses</h2>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DDiffie%E2%80%93H=
ellman_key_exchange&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D15" title=3D"Edit secti=
on: Other uses"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>]</span></span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Encryption">Encryption</h3>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DDiffie%E2%80%93H=
ellman_key_exchange&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D16" title=3D"Edit secti=
on: Encryption"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>]</span></span></div>
<p>Public key encryption schemes based on the Diffie=E2=80=93Hellman key ex=
change have been proposed. The first such scheme is the <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ElGamal_encryption" title=3D"ElGamal encryption">ElGa=
mal encryption</a>. A more modern variant is the <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Integrated_Encryption_Scheme" title=3D"Integrated Encryption=
 Scheme">Integrated Encryption Scheme</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Forward_secrecy">Forward se=
crecy</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brac=
ket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DDiffie=
%E2%80%93Hellman_key_exchange&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D17" title=3D"=
Edit section: Forward secrecy"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-edits=
ection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Protocols that achieve <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Forward_=
secrecy" title=3D"Forward secrecy">forward secrecy</a> generate new key pai=
rs for each <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Session_(computer_scie=
nce)" title=3D"Session (computer science)">session</a> and discard them at =
the end of the session. The Diffie=E2=80=93Hellman key exchange is a freque=
nt choice for such protocols, because of its fast key generation.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Password-authenticated_key_=
agreement">Password-authenticated key agreement</h3><span class=3D"mw-edits=
ection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DDiffie%E2%80%93Hellman_key_exchange&amp=
;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D18" title=3D"Edit section: Password-authentica=
ted key agreement"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brack=
et">]</span></span></div>
<p>When Alice and Bob share a password, they may use a <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Password-authenticated_key_agreement" title=3D"Passwor=
d-authenticated key agreement">password-authenticated key agreement</a> (PK=
) form of Diffie=E2=80=93Hellman to prevent man-in-the-middle attacks. One =
simple scheme is to compare the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cr=
yptographic_hash_function" title=3D"Cryptographic hash function">hash</a> o=
f <b>s</b> concatenated with the password calculated independently on both =
ends of channel. A feature of these schemes is that an attacker can only te=
st one specific password on each iteration with the other party, and so the=
 system provides good security with relatively weak passwords. This approac=
h is described in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ITU-T" title=3D"=
ITU-T">ITU-T</a> Recommendation <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/X.=
1035" title=3D"X.1035">X.1035</a>, which is used by the <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/G.hn" title=3D"G.hn">G.hn</a> home networking standar=
d.
</p><p>An example of such a protocol is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Secure_Remote_Password_protocol" title=3D"Secure Remote Password =
protocol">Secure Remote Password protocol</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Public_key">Public key</h3>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DDiffie%E2%80%93H=
ellman_key_exchange&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D19" title=3D"Edit secti=
on: Public key"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>]</span></span></div>
<p>It is also possible to use Diffie=E2=80=93Hellman as part of a <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Public_key_infrastructure" title=3D"Publi=
c key infrastructure">public key infrastructure</a>, allowing Bob to encryp=
t a message so that only Alice will be able to decrypt it, with no prior co=
mmunication between them other than Bob having trusted knowledge of Alice's=
 public key. Alice's public key is <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math=
-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y=
" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathM=
L" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle (g^{a}{\bmod {p}},g,p)}">
  <semantics>
